The aim of our study was to assess the prevalence, clinical characteristics and 
age of onset of allergic sensitization and clinical symptoms in a sample of 
atopic elders living in Campania region area (Southern Italy). Fourteen Allergy 
units or Centres examined a total of 462 patients. In this context 215 (46.53%) 
had positive skin prick tests (SPTs) to at least one allergen and were diagnosed 
with respiratory allergy. Parietaria represents the most common sensitizing 
agent in elders living in Campania region, followed by dust mites, grass pollen 
and Olea europaea. A relatively high percentage of atopic subjects suffered from 
respiratory symptoms at a fairly advanced age, namely 8.3% at 60-64 years, 10.2% 
at 65-70 and 5.7% at > 70 years. In conclusion, the prevalence and clinical 
significance of airway allergic sensitization in the elderly living in Campania 
region is more significant than expected in latter stages of life. Physicians 
should not neglect the role of atopy as a risk factor for the onset of allergic 
respiratory symptoms even in elderly patients.

