Exome sequencing of geographically diverse barley landraces and wild relatives 
gives insights into environmental adaptation.

Russell J(1), Mascher M(2)(3), Dawson IK(1), Kyriakidis S(1), Calixto C(4), 
Freund F(5), Bayer M(1), Milne I(1), Marshall-Griffiths T(1), Heinen S(6), 
Hofstad A(6), Sharma R(2)(4), Himmelbach A(2), Knauft M(2), van Zonneveld M(7), 
Brown JW(1)(4), Schmid K(5), Kilian B(2)(8), Muehlbauer GJ(6)(9), Stein N(2), 
Waugh R(1)(4).

Author information:
(1)Cell and Molecular Sciences, James Hutton Institute, Invergowrie, Dundee, UK.
(2)Leibniz Institute of Plant Genetics and Crop Plant Research (IPK), 
Gatersleben, Stadt Seeland, Germany.
(3)German Centre for Integrative Biodiversity Research (iDiv) 
Halle-Jena-Leipzig, Leipzig, Germany.
(4)Division of Plant Sciences, School of Life Sciences, University of Dundee, 
James Hutton Institute, Invergowrie, Dundee, UK.
(5)Department of Crop Biodiversity and Breeding Informatics, University of 
